<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5138&amp;p=46485#p46485</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5138&amp;p=46485#p46485"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: dubts about scanline, timming and better performance...]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5138&amp;p=46485#p46485"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">Disch wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br /><div class="quotetitle">dreampeppers99 wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">But ... isn't better just made logical operation with all addresses?<br /></div><br /><br />Usually, yes.  Conditionals are often slower than just doing a simple operation because they can disrupt the pipeline.  I would recommend ditching the if() statement in this case.<br /><br />Regarding the frame layout, it's something like this:<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">-------------------------------<br /> 1 &quot;Idle&quot; Scanline   &#40;aka, Scanline 240&#41;<br />-------------------------------   &lt;--- NMI occurs here, $2002.7 goes high here<br /> 20 scanlines of VBlank<br />-------------------------------   &lt;--- $2002 cleared here &#40;all 3 bits&#41;<br /> 1 &quot;Prerender&quot; Scanline &#40;aka, Scanline -1&#41;<br />-------------------------------<br /><br /> 240 rendered scanlines &#40;aka Scanlines 0-239&#41;<br /><br />-------------------------------<br /></div><br /><br />Since this is a repeating pattern, you may see it in a different order (VBlank at top, Idle at bottom).  It doesn't really matter what's on "top" as long as the order doesn't change.<br /><br />Every scanline is exactly 341 dots long (aka 341 PPU cycles).  The exception is the pre-render scanline which is sometimes 340 dots.<br /><br /><strong>VBlank</strong><br />Nothing happens.  PPU is not in rendering, safe to write to $2007, etc<br /><br /><strong>240 Rendered Scanlines</strong><br />Pixels output to the screen for dots 0-255.  PPU is constantly busy fetching data if rendering is enabled.  Not safe to write to $2007<br /><br /><strong>Prerender Scanline</strong><br /><em>Exactly</em> the same as a normal Rendered scanline in every way except for the following:<br /><br />1) No pixels output (but tiles are still fetched!)<br />2) Scroll Reset (loopy_v = loopy_t) occurs on dot 304 if rendering is enabled.  This is <em>in addition to</em> all of the other scroll changes made to loopy_v that take place during rendering time.<br /><br /><strong>Idle Scanline</strong><br />Same as VBlank (PPU effectively does nothing) -- but not really part of VBlank because NMI doesn't occur until after it.<br /><br /><br /><strong>Other Key Things To Note:</strong><br />- $2002.7 (VBlank flag) is raised on dot 0 of the first scanline of VBlank.  This is what triggers the NMI -- so NMI also occurs here.<br /><br />- All 3 bits of $2002 are cleared (VBlank flag, Sprite-0 hit, and sprite overflow) on dot 0 of the pre-render scanline (just as VBlank ends).<br /><br />- You never clear Sprite RAM<br /><br /><br /><br />I'm too lazy to go over all the details of what goes in during the scanline.  Maybe I'll post later -- or at least find a post where I (or someone else) went over all of this already (I know I have before)</div><br />Thanks very much for your effort and explanations here.  <img src="http://forums.nesdev.com/images/smilies/icon_biggrin.gif" alt=":D" title="Very Happy" /> <br />I was so fool when I think that if I could write one SChip8 emulator I would write an nes too... Now I'm seeing I realy don't know nothing about computers! (my initial goal was to have at least one game running within one mounth... :S) <br /><br />This is the kind of good pain ... I want to make it real, I'm on the way, without this community I probably would had stopped... Thanks you all<br /><br />(  I was wondering, the guy who made the first nes emulator IS A PERSON OUTSIDE OF NORMAL LIMITS )<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=912">dreampeppers99</a> — Sun May 03, 2009 4:09 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
